The crystal structures of disodium hydrogen citrate monohydrate, $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, and diammonium sodium citrate, $\left(\mathrm{NH}_{4}\right)_{2} \mathrm{NaC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$, have been solved and refined using laboratory $\mathrm{X}$-ray powder diffraction data, and optimized using density functional techniques. In $\mathrm{NaHC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, the $\mathrm{NaO}_{6}$ coordination polyhedra share edges, forming zigzag layers lying parallel to the $b c$ plane. The hydrophobic methylene groups occupy the interlayer spaces. The carboxylic acid group makes a strong charge-assisted hydrogen bond to the central carboxylate group. The hydroxyl group makes an intramolecular hydrogen bond to an ionized terminal carboxylate oxygen atom. Each hydrogen atom of the water molecule acts as a donor, to a terminal carboxylate and the hydroxyl group. Both the Na substructure and the hydrogen bonding differ from those of the known phase $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{1.5}$. In $\left(\mathrm{NH}_{4}\right)_{2} \mathrm{NaC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$, the $\mathrm{NaO}_{6}$ coordination octahedra share corners, making double zigzag chains propagating along the $b$-axis direction. Each hydrogen atom of the ammonium ions acts as a donor in a discrete $\mathrm{N}-\mathrm{H} \cdots \mathrm{O}$ hydrogen bond. The hydroxyl group forms an intramolecular $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} \cdots \mathrm{O}$ hydrogen bond to a terminal carboxylate oxygen atom.

\section{Chemical context}
A systematic study of the crystal structures of Group 1 (alkali metal) citrate salts has been reported in Rammohan \& Kaduk (2018). The study was extended to ammonium citrates in Wheatley \& Kaduk (2019). $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$ was an accidental product of an extension of the program to mixed ammonium-group 1 citrates, and $\left(\mathrm{NH}_{4}\right)_{2} \mathrm{NaC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ was an intended product. Another product in the series is $\left(\mathrm{NH}_{4}\right)_{2} \mathrm{KC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ (Patel et al., 2020). Known sodium citrates include two polymorphs of $\mathrm{NaH}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ (Rammohan \& Kaduk, 2016b; Glusker et al., 1965), $\mathrm{Na}_{2.5} \mathrm{H}_{0.5} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ (Rammohan \& Kaduk, 2017), $\quad \mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{1.5}$ (Rammohan \& Kaduk, 2016c), $\mathrm{Na}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$ (Rammohan \& Kaduk, 2016a), $\mathrm{Na}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{2}$ (Fischer \& Palladino, 2003), and $\mathrm{Na}_{3} \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{5.5}$ (Viossat et al., 1986).

As part of our ongoing studies in this area, we now report the syntheses and structures of disodium hydrogen citrate monohydrate, $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$, (I), and diammonium sodium citrate, $\left(\mathrm{NH}_{4}\right)_{2} \mathrm{NaC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}$, (II). $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$

