The CRYSTAL14 (Dovesi et al., 2014) energy per formula unit of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$ is $-1160.0 \mathrm{eV}$. The energy per formula unit of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HC}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{O}_{7}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{1.5}$ is $-1197.9 \mathrm{eV}$. Calculated in the same way, the energy of an isolated water molecule is $-76.4 \mathrm{eV}$. Thus, the energy of the sesquihydrate is thus $0.23 \mathrm{eV}$ higher than that of the sum of the monohydrate and half a water molecule. The difference is only $5.4 \mathrm{kcal} \mathrm{mol}^{-1}$, so the structures must be considered comparable in energy.

